{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e7ade3a5-865d-4a8f-ac77-a480a4c85d59","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- dotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**2. Find your process ID:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- dotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect the trace (30 seconds example):**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- dotnet-trace collect \\\n  -p <PID> \\\n  --profile cpu-sampling \\\n  --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**4. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**5. Analyze** by opening the `.nettrace` in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to speedscope:\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\n\n**Tips:**\n- If the container lacks the .NET SDK, use `dotnet tool install --tool-path /tmp dotnet-trace` instead.\n- For production, prefer `--duration` over interactive stop to avoid forgetting a running trace.\n- If `dotnet-trace` can't attach (e.g., musl/Alpine), fall back to **`perf`** or **`dotnet-counters`** to first confirm CPU is actually managed code.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6487e205-a031-4f2f-894f-7ebd8fb0f99b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I can answer this from knowledge without needing to look at any files.","outputTokens":428,"requestId":"AC0D:13323C:14C1832:1731BFB:6A067164"},"id":"556ea64d-5dea-45b7-bb6e-7ddb2c9f0ba8","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:05:49.932Z","parentId":"90dc07e1-66f1-4cf8-9c93-c259f09d18a8"}
